    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a really solid starting point for them. I want to make sure they understand why it's such a necessary check on power. Could you add a bit more about why the 'procedural' side of due process alone isn't enough to protect these kinds of fundamental rights? Basically, why is it dangerous if we only focus on the procedures and not the substance itself?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Relying only on procedural due process is insufficient because it only guarantees *how* the government acts, not *what* it is allowed to act upon. A government could follow all the proper legal steps—like holding a fair hearing—while still enacting a law that is fundamentally oppressive or violates basic human dignity. Substantive due process is necessary to act as a substantive check, ensuring that the *content* of the law itself aligns with core constitutional values, preventing the state from legally enshrining injustice.",
      "source": "target",
