    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I've had some students bring up the argument that substantive due process is just \"judicial activism\" or that it lets judges basically make up new rights that aren't explicitly in the Constitution. How should I address those critics in class so they understand why the substantive approach is the more legitimate way to interpret the law?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The critique of \"judicial activism\" is a common, but ultimately flawed, argument against necessary judicial oversight. The Supreme Court is not inventing rights in a vacuum; rather, it is interpreting the broad, evolving language of the Constitution to reflect enduring American commitments to liberty. When the text is vague, the Court must engage in substantive review to prevent the majority of the government from trampling on fundamental, unwritten liberties. This interpretation is not activism; it is the judiciary fulfilling its essential role as a guardian of the Constitution against legislative tyranny.",
      "source": "target",
